<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06296086 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06296086 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Lloyd Francis Jr. -- Mercury News; AMONG THE RUINS -- Residentsinspect the ruins of the Broadway Terrace district of Oakland, where the kindof fiery devastation that has claimed parts of the city is readily apparent.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  OAKLAND; FIRE; NEWS; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  On the job for less than a month, Oakland Fire Chief P. Lamont Ewell was justlearning the lay of the land when one of California's worst fires swept theOakland hills.;   Ewell, 38, had taken over as Oakland's chief after leaving ajob as assistant fire chief in Maryland.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  OAKLAND FIRE CHIEF FACES BLAZE WITH ONLY WEEKS ONTHE JOB  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  The Oakland Hills Fire; Notebook; See also related stories on pages 1A and14-20A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;It's difficult to come into a new organization and be faced with such anextreme task,&quot; said Fire Chief Steven Edwards, Ewell's old boss at the PrinceGeorge's County Fire Department in Maryland.;   &quot;But Lamont's a person who isvery much up to the challenge. It's a difficult situation that's been handledvery well,&quot; Edwards said on Monday.;   As deputy fire chief for the PrinceGeorge's County Fire Department for 2 1/2 years, Ewell oversaw specialoperations, including emergency medical service, fire prevention and fireinvestigation units.;   He departed for Oakland Sept. 27.;   &quot;Everybody backin Prince George County was sorry to see him leave,&quot; Edwards said.;   BeforeMaryland, Ewell worked at the Compton Fire Department for 12 years andeventually became deputy fire marshal.;   In Oakland, some say his style isalready making a statement.;   &quot;He's a very progressive fire chief. . . . Hedoes a good job,&quot; said Cpt. Charlie Fasso, a spokesman with the Oakland FireDepartment. &quot;He wants to modernize the department.&quot;; HAPPY ENDING TO FEARS OFNEWSPAPER REPORTER; Sunday night, Mercury News Staff Writer Pete Carey watchedhelplessly as flames danced along ridges near his father's home in the Oaklandhills.;   Pete and his brother, Scott, packed up as many of their father'sbelongings as they could, knowing they would have to leave family treasuresbehind.;   &quot;We may escape. We may be one of the lucky ones,&quot; Carey wrote inMonday morning's Mercury News.;   Monday, 87-year-old Paul Carey was indeedone of the lucky ones. His home was reported safe.;   &quot;The fire's out, but Istill carry it around,&quot; said Pete. &quot;Every time I close my eyelids, I still seeit.&quot;; GOURMET RESTAURANT BRINGS SANDWICHES TO SHELTERS; The Chez Panisserestaurant in Berkeley, renowned birthplace of California cuisine, reacted tothe blaze in style, delivering gourmet Italian focaccia sandwiches Monday toevacuees at shelters, according to general manager Richard Mazzera.;  &quot;Focaccia travels better,&quot; he said. &quot;It's easy to wrap.&quot;; GREAT CHICAGO FIREBARELY WORSE THAN OAKLAND'S; In dollar terms, the Oakland hills wildfirenearly rivals the devastation of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.;   Earlyestimates put the property damage in Oakland and neighboring Berkeley at $1.5billion.;   The National Fire Protection Association lists the fire loss ofthe historic Chicago blaze, in 1990 dollars, at $1.8 billion.;   Theassociation lists the 1871 Chicago catastrophe as the second-worst fire lossin U.S. history.;   The worst was from the huge fire that followed the SanFrancisco earthquake of 1906, when an estimated $5 billion in damageoccurred.;   The October 1989 earthquake in the San Francisco Bay Area causedan estimated $10 billion in damage, but relatively little was caused by fire.;  The association, a non-profit, business-supported organization that dealswith fire-safety issues, developed damage figures in 1990 dollars by applyingestimated inflation indexes to reported fire losses of the time.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911022  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  18A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  586  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 22, 199100296086,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>